description: 4 people in fancy attire sit behind a desk wearing gooseneck microphones, possibly in a game show or telethon. Behind them is a sign that reads in bold text "EMERGENCY HOTLINE". In front of them, a discheveled man in tattered clothes is crawling, looking up at them. The hosts are looking at the man with flat expressions. One host in the middle, a woman, leans over the desk with both hands, yelling angrily at the man crawling on the ground.
caption: This better be good. That floor was waxed last night!
element: The woman's callous attitude towards the man in need contradicts what we expect from an emergency hotline worker, who typically aims to be helpful
explanation: The joke hinges on misplaced priorities. An “EMERGENCY HOTLINE” crew should respond compassionately to desperate pleas, yet when a ragged man literally crawls to their desk for help, the woman in charge is peeved not about his crisis but about him dirtying their freshly waxed floor. Her warning—“This better be good”—treats life-or-death need like an entertainment audition, and the floor-wax complaint reduces the supposed life-saving setting to petty office housekeeping. The contrast between the high-stakes backdrop (emergency aid) and the trivial annoyance (scuffed wax) creates the humor.
autograder_reasoning: The student's answer effectively highlights the key comedic element of the cartoon: the contrast between the expected compassionate behavior of the emergency hotline worker and the woman's indifferent and trivial focus on the waxed floor. This discrepancy between expectation and reality is the root of the humor, matching the anticipated answer point.

description: 4 people in fancy attire sit behind a desk wearing gooseneck microphones, possibly in a game show or telethon. Behind them is a sign that reads in bold text "EMERGENCY HOTLINE". One host in the middle, a woman, leans over the desk with both hands, yelling angrily at the man crawling on the ground.
caption: Would it kill you to use a few of your roaming minutes?
element: The caption implies that the man is only visiting the hotline in person because it would have been an expensive phone call, a seemingly minor problem compared to whatever emergency the man is in
explanation:
The emergency-hotline panel expects people in crisis to phone in. Instead, a ragged, half-dead man has dragged himself there physically. The woman scolds him, “Would it kill you to use a few of your roaming minutes?” The joke lies in two layers: 

1) Cell-phone lingo: “roaming minutes” are the pricey minutes you use when your phone is outside its home network. People often avoid them to save money.  
2) Literal roaming: this man has truly “roamed” — he’s crawled who-knows-how-far to reach help.

The panelist absurdly prioritizes the trivial cost of cell service over the man’s obvious life-or-death need, and her phrase “Would it kill you…?” is darkly ironic because he looks as though it almost did. The clash between a dire emergency and the petty, corporate annoyance creates the humor.
autograder_reasoning: The student's answer captures the key comedic element by focusing on the absurdity of prioritizing the trivial cost of cell service over a life-or-death situation. The explanation about "roaming minutes" and the literal act of roaming, combined with the irony highlighted, aligns closely with the anticipated answer point regarding the expensive phone call versus the emergency situation.

explanation:
The scene evokes the stock opening of countless jokes—“A priest, a minister, and a rabbi walk into a bar.” When that trio shows up, people expect complicated theological debate or jokey one-liners. 2) In Catholic tradition there really was an official “Devil’s Advocate” who tried to poke holes in a candidate’s sainthood—a role priests would recognize.

So the caption melds the cliché bar-joke setup with the idiom, suggesting the bartender will spend the evening locked in head-spinning theological sparring with holy men, literally taking the Devil’s side for argument’s sake. The humor comes from that wordplay and from the weary resignation that this familiar joke scenario will turn his shift into a marathon debate session.
